      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Lee, let's talk about this knee\n\nFirst — I'm really glad you brought this up rather than just pushing through. Two weeks of sharp pain, especially on stairs, is your body sending a clear signal that deserves real attention.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: **diagnosing what's causing your knee pain is genuinely outside my lane as a coach.** Sharp pain that's persisted for two weeks, triggered by stairs and a long run, needs eyes from a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor — someone who can actually assess what's going on structurally. I'd be doing you a disservice if I guessed at a cause.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically — that's a medical decision, and I'd want you to get that guidance from a doctor or pharmacist rather than from me. What I *can* say is that using pain medication to mask symptoms in order to keep training is generally a pattern worth being cautious about, and worth raising directly with whoever you see.\n\n---\n\n**What I *can* do right now:**\n\nOnce you've seen a professional and have some clarity, I'm ready to work with you on whatever the path forward looks like — whether that's a modified plan, cross-training alternatives that keep your fitness while protecting the knee, or a revised timeline toward your July half marathon. A two-week setback at this stage of your build doesn't close the door on 1:45:00. What matters is getting the right information now so we don't turn a two-week issue into a two-month one.\n\n---\n\n**The clearest next step I can offer:** Book an appointment with a physio or sports medicine doctor this week if you can — ideally someone with experience working with runners.\n\nWhen you have some answers, come back and we'll figure out the plan together. What does your access to sports medicine or physio look like right now?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01N42Mcu7mXvFURsgMfSSmj1"
    }
